---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout>
    <section style="padding-top: 60px; border-bottom: none;">
        <div class="container reading" style="max-width: var(--container);">
            <span class="tag sanskrit">॥ यात्रा ज्ञानस्य ॥</span>
            <span class="tag">Story</span>
            <h1>My <span class="highlight">Journey</span></h1>
            <p class="lead" style="max-width: 650px;">
                Most people tell you where they studied, where they worked, what they achieved. This is not that kind of story. This is a story about curiosity, constraints, and a long search for understanding.
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section style="padding-top: 40px; border-bottom: none;">
        <div class="container reading" style="max-width: var(--container);">
            <h2>The Beginning</h2>
            <p>One of my earliest memories is taking things apart. Toys rarely stayed intact. I wanted to see what was inside, how the pieces connected, why the system worked the way it did. I usually couldn't put them back together. But the question stayed: How does this work?</p>

            <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Childhood & Observation</h2>
            <p>When I was four years old, my mother passed away. Life changed. I moved to my grandparents' home in Kohrana, a small village in Rajasthan.</p>
            <p>I was extremely introverted. Rarely spoke. Spent most of my time observing rather than participating. But I also got access to the internet early. My physical world was small. My digital world was expanding.</p>
            <p>As I grew older, I noticed a pattern: people accepted things as they were. I wanted to understand why they were that way. Why do schools work like this? Why do businesses fail? Why do some ideas spread and others die? I rarely found satisfying answers.</p>

            <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The Turning Point</h2>
            <p>In 9th class, I was forced into a school competition. Topic: Swami Vivekananda's biography. We got the book one month before. I didn't open it.</p>
            <p>The night before the competition, at 8 PM, I finally opened it. I couldn't stop reading. I read all night. I didn't go to the competition the next morning. But by sunrise, I had finished the book.</p>
            <p>That night changed something. I realized I did have an interest in learning. But I also realized: the way I was being taught wasn't working for me. I never wrote what teachers wrote. I understood the chapter and wrote it in my own words — my own structure, my own language. In 9th grade science, I scored full marks. Not because I memorized. Because I understood. I learned best by understanding deeply, not by repetition.</p>

            <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The Math That Changed Everything</h2>
            <p>In 2015, I completed 10th class. I was 15. I did the math: if I followed the conventional path, I'd start my career in my mid-20s. I decided to start early.</p>
            <p>I went to my maternal uncle in Pali. Convinced him to help me find work. Packed my bags. Booked a ticket to Vishakhapatnam — 1,300 km away from home. Then the call came. The employer asked: "What is your age?" I told him. He explained child labor laws. "We cannot hire anyone below 18." All my plans collapsed in a single phone call.</p>
            <p>I switched off my phone. Stayed with friends for 4-5 days. Then went back home. I waited. I turned 18. Completing 12th grade took an additional year. I didn't want to go to college. I had seen enough. It felt like a waste of life. So I chose a different path.</p>

            <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The Lockdown — The Crucible</h2>
            <p>In 2020, while working in hospitality, I started searching for skills I could learn without a degree. That search led me to digital marketing. I joined a digital marketing institute. ₹30,000 for 3 months. ₹25,000 in my account.</p>
            <p>The lockdown extended. 1 month. 2 months. 3 months. I was living in a rented building in Delhi. 8,000 rent. My room partner left. The building caretaker left. I was alone. For one month, I was the only person in that entire building.</p>
            <p>Friends came when I had money. When the money ran out, they stopped coming. Relatives in Delhi refused to take me in. Fear of COVID. One month of complete isolation. No human contact. No income. No support. Just me and my thoughts.</p>
            <p>That month changed something. I started reading — Ramayana, Mahabharata, Bhagavad Gita. Not as religion. As frameworks for understanding. Isolation affects people differently. In my case, it forced me to confront questions I had been avoiding.</p>

            <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The Vow</h2>
            <p>I had experienced how expensive knowledge was. Digital marketing courses cost 90,000. I couldn't afford that. I paid 5,000 and couldn't finish the course because I lost my job.</p>
            <p>When I found a 9,999 course, I jumped at it. I bought the course. I never sold it. Because I realized: I hadn't understood digital marketing yet. I was still learning. How could I teach something I hadn't mastered?</p>
            <p>I made a commitment: I would never sell what I didn't understand. I borrowed a laptop from a friend. I kept learning. Kept building. Kept experimenting.</p>

            <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">A Bigger Question</h2>
            <p>While exploring different fields, I noticed something strange. Engineers used one language. Doctors used another. Economists used another. Yet they were all describing the same reality. The words changed. The patterns often did not.</p>
            <p>That observation led to a question: If reality is one, why is understanding divided into so many disconnected subjects? I was no longer searching for a skill. I was searching for foundations.</p>
            <p>LucentHindu emerged from that shift. Not as a business plan. Not as a personal brand. But as a place to organize ideas, document observations, build systems, and share what I learn.</p>

            <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The Operating Years</h2>
            <p>From 2018 to 2026, I worked across Aerocity's busiest hotels — Holiday Inn, ibis, Vivanta by Taj, Pullman, Novotel. One employer. Ashoka Tours and Travels.</p>
            <ul class="structural">
                <li><strong style="color: var(--text);">Front Desk:</strong> Guest consultation, sales, relationship building, chauffeur allocation, escalation handling.</li>
                <li><strong style="color: var(--text);">Car Desk:</strong> High-volume vehicle dispatch, crew logistics, operational coordination.</li>
                <li><strong style="color: var(--text);">Sales:</strong> Closed 50+ premium tour packages. Highest booking: 60,000.</li>
                <li><strong style="color: var(--text);">Logistics:</strong> Coordinated IndiGo crew rotations — 40+ crew members, 6 vehicles, strict airport cut-off times.</li>
                <li><strong style="color: var(--text);">Team:</strong> Managed 8-25 chauffeurs per shift.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>These years taught me what operations actually look like when they scale.</p>

            <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">LucentHindu — The Foundation</h2>
            <p>I acquired the LucentHindu domain in 2021. From 2021 to 2025, I spent time reading, researching, and experimenting — understanding systems, information architecture, and how digital presence, knowledge, and operations actually work.</p>
            <p>In 2026, I began building LucentHindu as a platform for systems research, documentation, and consulting.</p>

            <div style="margin-top: 2rem; background: var(--surface); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">
                <h3 style="font-size: 1.1rem;">Timeline</h3>
                <ul class="structural">
                    <li><strong>2004</strong> — Lost mother. Moved to Kohrana, Rajasthan.</li>
                    <li><strong>2015</strong> — Attempted to start work. Stopped by child labor laws.</li>
                    <li><strong>2018</strong> — Entered hospitality operations with Ashoka Tours & Travels.</li>
                    <li><strong>2020</strong> — Lockdown, isolation, self-directed learning, and the vow.</li>
                    <li><strong>2021</strong> — Acquired the LucentHindu domain and began independent research.</li>
                    <li><strong>2026</strong> — Concluded hospitality operations after eight years.</li>
                    <li><strong>2026 - Present</strong> — Building LucentHindu as a platform for systems research, documentation, and consulting.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Where I Stand</h2>
            <p>This page is not a resume. It is a record. A footprint of where I started, what I learned, what I explored, developed, and began building.</p>
            <p>Every engagement begins with understanding. This is my understanding of where I stand.</p>
        </div>
    </section>
</Layout>